From then a gradual movement from CO1 to P40A - this continued to the Point where over 150 birds had flown to P40A - only 40 were left in the Creek. However there was still some movement across the Creek with birds going to CO1 to drink. Work started at 8:00 on Tipner, a large crash at one point caused the birds in the closest creek to fly to CO1. When birds flew to P40A they flew in a crescent, entering the site where there was a gap between tall trees

As the tide rose and covered the intertidal, birds swam to the area (CO4) just off P40 - they were alert as if wanting to get onto the field, but with a constant stream of activity they didn't do it whilst I was watching

As I arrived at Southsea Common (P35) birds were flushed from the east of the war memorial. 13 landed back on the common west of memorial, but 11 flew to Gilkicker. - I phoned Dave S who had just counted the flock in the area I thought they had land, he went back recounted and number had increased by 10 birds.

A Johnson phoned to advise that he had a Black Brant back at Tournebury on Hayling Island. The bird I had seen at P29 was not present - suspect same bird as very few recorded in the county this winter
